			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: The Only Reason I Play EverQuest --&amp;gt; Bard :)<a name="52614"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 19 04 11:05 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Disclaimer:  Most things expressed in this post are merely opinions, so please do not take them as fact!
<br />

<br />
-----------------------------------------------------------
<br />

<br />
1. Defense, get as much as you can in it.  You probably won't spend a lot of time tanking because we tank worse than rangers... but you'll still get hit.  I swarm kited pretty much from 39 to 65 so my defense was pretty pitiful.  Once you hit 60 the fastest way I found to fix it was to use Kazumi's (lvl 60 bard invul song) and pull 30ish blue mobs and let them all swing away.
<br />

<br />
2.  I found cha and int to be the most important, but again, I used them for swarm kiting.  If you usually group then you would probably want different stats.  The only stat I wouldn't waste my time on is wisdom.
<br />

<br />
As for Singing Steel, most of them can be useful for the clicky/worn effects.  I had the bp, boots, bracer, and gloves just for the effects.  There are much better items to be worn, but you can always carry around a piece of SS in your inventory and only put it on long enough to clicky it.
<br />

<br />
3.  It all depends on the group and what you are fighting.
<br />

<br />
4.  To bind a skill to an arrow key, you just have to go to the options (ctrl - o), select the keyboard tab, select macros from the select category drop-down box.  Let's assume that you put foraging in hot button slot 1. Click on the line for hot button 1 where it says '-----' under the 'Alternate' column.  Now push the up arrow.   Close the options window.
<br />

<br />
Now whenever you push up, whatever skill is in hotbutton slot 1 will be used.  I'm sure there are more advanced ways to do it with a button using /doability, but this is the easiest way without writing out a button macro.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
