			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: The Only Reason I Play EverQuest --&amp;amp;gt; Bard :)<a name="52623"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 19 04 12:14 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Here's my advice on playing a bard, especially at low level.
<br />

<br />
1 Defense.  Defense is a hard skill to practice especially if your not the tank.  However, your skill will go up in time, especially if you start to fill the roles of puller and crowd control.  You will inevitebly get hit and the more you get hit the better your skills become.  The easist way to up your skill is simply to let it happen.  Or to keep an eye out for mosters that you can solo using melee skills.   
<br />

<br />
2 Stats.  The most important stat for all classes is hit points.  When it comes to fighting mosters, the one who lasts is the one who wins.  HP will forgive low resists, low ac, low int, mana, etc etc(and of course Defense).  That's not to say those skills aren't important, but HP should be what you focus on.  Get as many hp/sta items as you can focusing on HP as eventually you'll have max stamina, and replace stamina items with HP items.  As a bard twisting songs and mezzing/charming mobs will be your defining abilities.  As a result you should look very hard at Charisma.  Charisma affects your missed notes, and it affects resists on charm, mez, &amp; lull.  All other stats will follow if you focus on HP, Sta &amp; Cha.  Intelligence and Dexterity are things to keep an eye on when your torn between HP/sta/cha items.
<br />

<br />
3. Song lineup.  Pretty much my entire career, I've always played 2 types of songs consistently, and one flavor song.  You will always play a mana song, whether it's level 16 or 32 mana, or at higher levels hp regen/mana songs.  Regardless, mana is allways on my playlist even when I'm solo'ing (high end mana songs add a lot of hp regen).  Second is some sort of haste/melee buff.  I could write a thesis on the importance of haste and attack, but instead I'll just link a great source of information on haste, how it works and let you then understand why you should always have the max haste possible (unless your the tank, it's more important to hit harder and slower so you get riposted less, but that's mostly endgame and not a bard issue for the most part).
<br />

<br />
http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallfrm8.showMessage?topicID=99.topic
<br />

<br />
Finally the third slot is one that will pretty much change depending on the situation, you may be the only slower/snarer in the group, so that will be your 3rd song, you may want to add extra regen, it completely depends on your level, the situation, and the songs you have in your arsenal at the time.  An excellent standby is slow/snare if your not sure.  Oh, and do not overlook fear, not getting hit is the best offense.  Just make sure someone snares.
<br />

<br />
Hope that helps.  There is soo much more, but that should keep you busy for quite a while.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=182896">Fernwillow Feyd`Akin</a><br></span></td>
