		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: The Only Reason I Play EverQuest --&gt; Bard :)<a name="52706"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 19 04 7:19 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>First of all welcome to the boards Ashlii! It is always nice to see new people posting here. But without further ado:-
<br />

<br />
1: Defence is important to every class, but even more so to classes that have a realistic chance of mitigating a significant portion of a mob's damage. As a bard you will get hit on occasion, not as much as a warrior or an enchanter, but enough to give it serious consideration.
<br />

<br />
Because Defence also directly adjusts your AC it also has an effect on the equipment choices you have available to you (see 2).
<br />

<br />
The way to raise it is to simply get hit by blue and above mobs. Certain high cyans may also give imps, but for the most part stick with blues for this. The same also applies to raising melee stats - just hit them and eventually they will start catching up.
<br />

<br />
Oh yes, an additional tip for raising melee skills, always use your fastest weapon in your offhand until Dual Wield is maxed for your level. After that transfer it (or whichever skill you want to raise most) to your primary hand. This maximises the number of swings you get per level helping the imp rate over time.
<br />

<br />
2: This used to be a key question within bard circles, and it's still misunderstood now by many. The simple truth is that there are different styles of playing a bard, and these affect equipment choices. First of all I'll mention solo bards. This is not you but they do tend to have specific areas to concentrate on, namely mana regen, HP regen, cha and HP.
<br />

<br />
For more group-oriented bards there are 2 completely different approaches. The traditional way was for bards to concentrate on cha and HP, and then add AC and resists as a secondary concern. This approach sometimes means having to use a lower aggro twist than might be optimal, but does make for a consistent puller or crowd controller in a group that can keep the bard from being hit.
<br />

<br />
The alternative style is to concentrate on AC, with cha and HP of secondary importance. The point of this approach is to be able to take a few hits where necessary without being a mana sponge. This means you can play very high aggro twists with more safety, and also means that bad pulls of mez/charm resists are more survivable.
<br />

<br />
Personally I was a bard of the latter type, and it is still my belief that this style is best for low level bards. However, I will add a caveat to the AC style. At higher levels the effects af AC start to diminish significantly for bards. My advice to AC bards would be to go for AC up to lvl50 and then to gradually convert over to HP between 50 and 60. Ideally you should keep your AC around the 1200 mark buffed.
<br />

<br />
Above lvl60 most bards will stress the importance of HP over anything, at least unless you are acting as a full-time puller, in which case the argument for cha increases.
<br />

<br />
3: OK, I will go through these things one at a time and point out some different options. First of all nearly all bards will play a haste and a slow as 2 of their songs if these roles are not covered by another group member. Even if there is a chanter or shammy in the grp it is often better to let the bard handle 1 or both of these roles. For the 3rd song some form of dmg (eg fufil when you get it) or damage mitigation (hymn, resists) is normal. In a group where hastes and slows are covered you are essentially just acting as dps or dmg mitigation and choose songs accordingly.
<br />

<br />
Now let's come to the situation of a multi-mob pull. First of all let's say you have 2 mobs. Most bards in this situation would automatically mez or charm the add and then play a couple of key alternative songs. Bards that have learnt the skill will probably also melee whilst doing this.
<br />

<br />
But that is by no means the only way of handling the situation. An alternative can be to use an AE slow (largo) and simply let the add hit you whilst you kill the first mob as quickly as possible. A variation on this is to use AE tactics and sing a twist such as DDD+CoD+largo+hymn whilst juggling instruments. At your current lvl (24) this approach is often more efficient than using crowd control.
<br />

<br />
Now let's move to the 3 mob situation. Here you have 3 main options. The first is to mez the 2 adds and throw in 1 or 2 extra songs when resist rates allow. I would not recommend trying to melee with this technique, your primary responsibility is to control.
<br />

<br />
The second method is to charm 1 add and have it attack the other add. The primary target is then moved away from the pet allowing the 2 adds to fight between themselves. You should then melee, the idea being to kill of the first target around the time the charm breaks, restoring the situation to the 2-mob situation above.
<br />

<br />
Finally you can still use AE tactics with you (the bard) tanking the additional 2 unless there is a spare tank in the group. Naturally the more adds you tank the more difficulty involved so it is nice to know you have a half-decent healer before you take this approach with 3+. However, it is surprising just how much AE dps a bard can output in this way.
<br />

<br />
A last tie up here between your 3 questions. To be able to use the AE approach successfully you need to reach a certain level of AC where a large portion of the mob's melee dps is mitigated. This is sometimes called the AC threshold and raises as you fight more difficult mobs.
<br />

<br />
That has a knock-on to question 2 in equipment choices. You have to be an AC bard to use these high aggro methods or you are simply taking too much dmg to make the technique worth it. Finally even if you are decked out in AC gear, if your Defence remains behind you will still be below the AC threshold. Defence is an absolutely key skill for any bard looking to have a high AC.
<br />

<br />
So to answer your equipment questions I have to return the question back to you. What do you want to be able to do with your bard? What is your intuition on how to handle the situation you described? And what is your overall style of play? It's in answering these questions that you can answer the central question on just what it is you want to spend your pp on.
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
